        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-06-29T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-06-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="655" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d655">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">852.00/6–2948</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by Mr. William B. Dunham of the
                        Division of Western European Affairs</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-06-29">June 29,
                            1948</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <table>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Participants:</cell>
                        <cell>Mr. Baraibar, Chargé d’Affaires of the Spanish Embassy</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell>Mr. Achilles, Chief, <gloss target="#t_WE1">WE</gloss>
                        </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell>Mr. Dunham, <gloss target="#t_WE1">WE</gloss>
                        </cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <p>During his call this morning, Mr. Baraibar was shown a copy of a telegram<note n="1" xml:id="d655fn1">Not printed.</note> from Mr. Culbertson in which he
                    reported that he had been informed by the Foreign Minister that the Spanish
                    Government expects to announce within the next few weeks the holding of
                    municipal elections in Spain sometime during October or November.</p>
                <p>Mr. Achilles said this was a very hopeful sign and he hoped the Spanish
                    Government would go through with this action. He felt that any measures taken by
                    the Spanish Government to dramatize the elections would be helpful in indicating
                    to the world that Spain, in its own way and its own time, was moving in the
                    direction of more liberal domestic policies. He mentioned to Mr. Baraibar that
                    any of these actions taken before the forthcoming General Assembly in Paris
                    would undoubtedly have a beneficial effect.</p>
            </div>
